        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=39247&amp;TOPIC_ID=4931&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=What+was+DAoC%27s+downfall%3F&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         I still play it occasionally, although my necromancer-equivalent classes (Spiritmaster and Cabalist) don't have the appeal of the true necromancer.  My main ended up being a rogue (Nightshade).</P><P>I think the main point in comparing the two games is to realize that they're built with different design philosophies.  I'm not sure quite how to phrase it but... EQ is a very fleshed-out RPG.  DAOC is somewhere between EQ and Diablo.</P><P>The DAOC interface is certainly a lot better - it's nicer to look at, and anything I want to do from trade skills to quests to interacting with other PCs is easier in DAOC.  Melee combat is better and much more interesting.  Realm vs. Realm combat is a great PvP foundation.  On the whole, the graphics are better.  Little things that occasionally annoy me in EQ are gone - spell swapping, research/dropped spells, green aggro.  Because of the skill system, there's usually some variation possible within classes that adds flavor.</P><P>EQ has a much larger, much more diverse world by any measure.  Spellcasters in EQ get a huge selection of spell lines compared to the DAOC casters, including quite a lot more utility/fun spells.  EQ faction interplay is a world in itself.  Norrath geography is more varied and generally more interesting, even if it isn't quite as pretty.  EQ has much stronger historic storylines, and many more of them.</P><P>In general, DAoC fights are over fast and downtime is low, so you can actually "play" the game without as much setup time or hassle; on the other hand, the enemies (for the most part) don't seem to be as interesting or as diverse. My nightshade can kill two siabra in the time it takes my necromancer to kill a single shardworm and then kill two more siabra in the time it takes to get my mana/health back - but killing the shardworm is more satisfying somehow.</P><P>They're both good games, they're just different.</P><P><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=247832" target="_blank">Morty Undercrypt</a>, Keeper of the <a href="http://www.necrognomicon.com/" target="_blank">NecroGnomicon</a><BR><font size=1>"I am the truth, and the truth shall make you flee."</font id=size1><BR>E'ci<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

